--- !u!114 &974258906
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 974258903}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: fcb87846e43a704469d9be7ef4faa09a, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  _Source: "The pope is the bishop of Rome and the [visible head](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Head_of_the_Church#Catholic_Church)
    of the worldwide [Catholic Church](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catholic_Church)
    . He is also known as the supreme pontiff , Roman pontiff , or sovereign pontiff
    . From the 8th century until 1870, the pope was the [sovereign](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sovereign)
    or [head of state](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Head_of_state) of the [Papal
    States](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Papal_States) , and since 1929 of the much
    smaller [Vatican City](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vatican_City) state. From
    a Catholic viewpoint, the [primacy of the bishop of Rome](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primacy_of_the_bishop_of_Rome)
    is largely derived from his role as the [apostolic successor](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apostolic_successor)
    to [Saint Peter](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saint_Peter) , to whom [primacy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petrine_primacy)
    was conferred by [Jesus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jesus) , who gave Peter
    the [Keys of Heaven](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keys_of_Heaven) and the powers
    of \\\"binding and loosing\\\", naming him as the \\\"rock\\\" upon which the
    Church would be built. The current pope is [Leo XIV](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leo_XIV)
    , who was elected on 8 May 2025 on the second day of the [2025 papal conclave](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2025_papal_conclave)
    .\\n\\nAlthough his office is called the papacy , the [jurisdiction](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ecclesiastical_jurisdiction)
    of the [episcopal see](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Episcopal_see) is called
    the [Holy See](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Holy_See) . The word see comes from
    the Latin for 'seat' or 'chair' ( sede , referring in particular to the one on
    which the newly elected pope sits during the enthronement ceremony). It is the
    Holy See that is the [sovereign entity](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sovereign_entity)
    under [international law](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_law) headquartered
    in the distinctively independent Vatican City, a [city-state](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/City-state)
    which forms a geographical [enclave](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enclave) within
    the conurbation of [Rome](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rome) , established by
    the [Lateran Treaty](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lateran_Treaty) in 1929 between
    [Fascist Italy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fascist_Italy) and the Holy See
    to ensure its [temporal](https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/temporal) and spiritual
    independence. The Holy See is recognized by its adherence at various levels to
    international organizations and by means of its diplomatic relations and political
    accords with many independent states.\\n\\nAccording to [Catholic tradition](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catholic_tradition)
    , the [apostolic see](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apostolic_see) of [Rome](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diocese_of_Rome)
    was founded by [Saint Peter](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saint_Peter) and [Saint
    Paul](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saint_Paul) in the first century. The papacy
    is one of the most enduring institutions in the world and has had a prominent
    part in [human history](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_history) . In ancient
    times, the popes helped spread Christianity and intervened to find resolutions
    in various doctrinal disputes. In the [Middle Ages](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle_Ages)
    , they played a role of secular importance in Western Europe, often acting as
    arbitrators between Christian monarchs. In addition to the expansion of [Christian
    faith and doctrine](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christian_theology) , modern
    popes are involved in [ecumenism](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ecumenism) and
    [interfaith dialogue](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interfaith_dialogue) , [charitable
    work](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catholic_charities) , and the defence of
    human rights.\\n\\nOver time, the papacy accrued [broad secular and political
    influence](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temporal_power_of_the_Holy_See) , eventually
    rivalling those of territorial rulers. In recent centuries, the temporal authority
    of the papacy has declined and the office is now largely focused on religious
    matters. By contrast, papal claims of spiritual authority have been increasingly
    firmly expressed over time, culminating in 1870 with the proclamation of the
    [dogma](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catholic_dogma) of [papal infallibility](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Papal_infallibility)
    for rare occasions when the pope speaks [ex cathedra](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ex_cathedra)
    \u2014literally 'from the [chair (of Saint Peter)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chair_of_Saint_Peter)
    '\u2014to issue a formal definition of [faith](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dogma)
    or morals. The pope is considered one of the world's most powerful people due
    to the extensive diplomatic, cultural, and spiritual influence of his position
    on both 1.3 billion Catholics and those outside the Catholic faith, and because
    he heads the world's largest non-government provider of [education](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catholic_school)
    and [health care](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catholic_Church_and_health_care)
    , with a vast network of charities."
  RenderSettings:
    Bold:
      RenderBold: 1
